Boats Segmentation: Factor Analysis

Team Names: Anubhav Raina, Alican Ulke, Juan Pablo Valdes, Elena Minardi, Zagita Truhandiaz

Business Decisions

Our boat company is looking to isolate factors based on customer survey data. The isolated factors will then be used to build customer segments to enable us to appropriately identify target markets for our different offerings.

The Data

The data below contains customer responses to 29 questions about their boating habits based on a 5-point rating scale.

This is how the first 50 data looks:

Our Approach

Factor Analysis in 6 steps

  1. Confirm the data in metric

  2. Decide whether to scale or standardize the data

  3. Check the correlation matrix to see if Factor Analysis makes sense

  4. Develop a scree plot and decide on the number of factors to be derived

  5. Interpret the factors and consider factor rotations (technical but useful)

  6. Save factor scores for subsequent analyses

Let's follow these steps.

Step 2: Decide whether to scale or standardize the data

We have decided to standardize the data to ease calculations. 

ProjectDatafactor_scaled = apply(ProjectDataFactor, 2, function(r) {
    if (sd(r) != 0) 
        res = (r - mean(r))/sd(r) else res = 0 * r
    res
})

5. Interpret the factors and consider factor rotations (technical but useful)

Intepretation, Decisions and Conclusion

Based on the factor analysis, big bulk of the customers fall into one of the few large segments and the rest fall into one of the many very small segments that all together make 14 segments in total. It is because of this reason, we had to pull together many factors to explain %75 of the variation in the gathered data. The manufacturer of the boat will have a challenging time addressing all the customers since they vary so much. Clever targeted marketing must be done to optimize marketing budget for such a varied customer base.

The large segments are (3 or more Questions per Factor):
1. Boat Lovers
Distinguishing Question: Boating is the number one thing I do in my spare time
2. Nautical Performance Lovers
Distinguishing Question: When buying accessories for my boat I tend to buy the latest and greatest
3. Nature Seekers, who see the boat an escape strategy from their busy lives
Distinguishing Question: Boating allows me to experience nature
4. Status conscious, ambitious high achievers
Distinguishing Question: Owning a boat gives me a sense of achievement

Smaller Segments are (2 or less Questions per Factor):
5. Whatever floats my boat, price conscious
Distinguishing Question: When buying a boat getting the lowest price is more important than the boat brand
6. The Mechanic who enjoys working on his/her boat
Distinguishing Question: I tend to perform minor boat repairs and maintenance on my own
7. Non-impulse buyer, who likes to visually compare all options before making final decision
Distinguishing Question: When buying a boat I do a lot of shopping around and visit multiple dealers
8. Whatever floats my boat, brand conscious
Distinguishing Question: I only consider buying a boat from a reputable brand
9. Function over form
Distinguishing Question: When buying a boat functionality is more important than style
10. Non-expert boater, who still depends on expert knowledge before making a final decision
Distinguishing Question: When buying a boat I rely more on expert opinion than my own e g consumer reports salespeople
11. Casual Boater
Distinguishing Question: Boating is one of many things I do in my spare time
12. Social Boater, boating as a mean to socialize with people
Distinguishing Question: Boating gives me an outlet to socialize with family and or friends
13. No Explanatory Power
14. Water Sports Lover, boating as a mean to do other water sports
Distinguishing Question: Boating allows me to excel in the sports that I am passionate about e g fishing racing water sports
